# Refresh routing

`ChatIndex.ensure_current` in
`cursor_view/chat_index/index.py` is the canonical switch for deciding
which refresh recipe runs against the cache. It picks between three
paths:

- **Synchronous delta** (caller blocks while the existing
  per-composer diff and apply pass run end-to-end) is the
  manual-refresh path: `force=True` from the home page Refresh
  button. The work routes through
  `ChatIndex._run_synchronous_delta_or_rebuild`, which is the
  shared helper the SWR background worker also calls into so the
  manual and background entry points cannot drift on what counts
  as a recoverable apply-time failure. The helper falls back to a
  full rebuild on the same correctness signals listed below
  (missing cache, unreadable `meta`, schema drift) plus any
  `sqlite3.DatabaseError` raised by `compute_source_diff` /
  `apply_delta` itself.
- **Synchronous rebuild** (caller blocks until the new cache is
  ready) runs on:
  - missing cache file (first-build);
  - cache that raises `sqlite3.DatabaseError` while its `meta`
    rows are being read (corruption);
  - `schema_version` meta row that does not match
    `INDEX_SCHEMA_VERSION` (schema drift).

  These are the correctness-gated triggers that the synchronous
  delta arm escalates to via the shared helper, and that
  `ensure_current`'s non-force arms hit directly.
- **Stale-while-revalidate** (caller is handed the current
  snapshot, a background worker refreshes off the request path)
  runs when the only signal is a source-DB fingerprint miss; the
  on-disk row shapes are still current, so serving them until the
  refresh lands is safe.

Note: `force=True` used to drive a synchronous full rebuild
unconditionally. It now drives a synchronous **delta** with the
full-rebuild fallback above, because the home page Refresh button
should not pay the build-to-temp + atomic-swap cost on every
click when an incremental apply would suffice.

# Invariant: never serve rows under a different schema version

Do not add a condition to `_cached_index_up_to_date` that returns
`False` without first deciding which of the three dispatch paths
above it belongs on. The deciding question is "does this change
affect row **shape** or just row **freshness**?". Shape drift
(columns added/removed, semantics changed, FTS schema rewritten)
is a correctness bug if the cache is served during the rebuild
and must route through the synchronous-rebuild branch (or, on
the manual-refresh arm, escalate from synchronous-delta to
synchronous-rebuild via the shared helper's correctness-gate
fallback). Freshness drift (source DB mtimes moved, content
hashes changed) is safe to serve stale and should stay on SWR so
the API latency stays bounded.

The `_cached_schema_version` helper exists specifically so the
router can distinguish the two without reading the `meta` table
twice; keep it as the single source of truth for the
`schema_version` comparison rather than re-reading `meta` inline.
The source-fingerprint hash in `fingerprint.py` already folds
`INDEX_SCHEMA_VERSION` into its SHA-256, so the two signals flip in
lockstep on a ship; the direct read is what lets `ensure_current`
pick synchronous vs. background before dispatch.

# Related rules and code

- Cache table layout, history of schema bumps, and the
  synchronous-vs-SWR summary that this rule points back to:
  [`sqlite-cursor-db.mdc`](sqlite-cursor-db.mdc).
- Canonical routing switch: `ChatIndex.ensure_current` in
  `cursor_view/chat_index/index.py`.
- Shared apply-time helper that the manual-refresh and
  background-refresh paths both call into (and that owns the
  delta-with-rebuild-fallback contract):
  `ChatIndex._run_synchronous_delta_or_rebuild` in the same module.
- Regression guards:
  `tests/test_chat_index_incremental.py::test_schema_version_bump_forces_synchronous_rebuild`
  and `::test_source_fingerprint_bump_uses_background_refresh` lock
  down the schema-drift and SWR sides of the routing decision;
  `::test_force_refresh_uses_delta_path`,
  `::test_force_refresh_falls_back_to_rebuild_on_apply_error`, and
  `::test_force_refresh_recovers_from_corrupt_meta` lock down the
  synchronous-delta arm, its apply-time rebuild fallback, and the
  pre-check's swallow-and-continue handling of a corrupt cache
  (so a stale `meta` table never surfaces as a 500 from the
  manual-refresh path).
